Introduction¶

Trading financial products is a highly intricate and multifaceted activity that involves a variety of elements. The financial product market offers a wide range of options such as stocks, bonds, foreign exchange, commodity futures, each with unique features that require specific trading strategies and techniques. These financial products operate within distinct markets, where prices are in constant flux based on market movements that are influenced by various factors such as economic indicators, corporate performance announcements, and changes in political situations. Precisely predicting these factors and trading accordingly is vital for success in trading. Moreover, financial product trading entails inherent risks, with the possibility of losses due to price fluctuations. Investors undertake various risk management strategies such as portfolio diversification or stop-loss orders to limit losses. Some financial products even allow for leverage, which can amplify risks. In addition, trading financial products involves several stakeholders, including financial institutions, investors, and regulatory authorities, leading to the presence of complex rules and procedures that must be followed. Considering all these factors, trading financial products is undoubtedly a complex and demanding activity. Achieving success in this field requires investors to have accurate judgments about market trends and risks based on their knowledge and experience.¶

What are S&P 500, XLY, XLV, XLRE and so on?¶

The S&P 500 is a benchmark consisting of 500 large publicly traded companies in the US, serving as an essential indicator for investors to evaluate the general health of the US stock market and determine whether it is overheating or not. Some investors also purchase funds that are linked to the index. On the other hand, XLY, XLV, and XLRE are exchange-traded funds (ETFs) that follow the performance of distinct sectors of the S&P 500. XLY keeps track of the consumer discretionary sector, which includes Amazon and Disney, while XLV monitors the healthcare sector, which includes Johnson & Johnson and Pfizer. With eight other unique ETFs tracking various sectors of the S&P 500, investors can acquire exposure to specific sectors of the index. By investing in these ETFs, investors can invest in specific sectors of the S&P 500 index.¶
These are the 10 different sectors of S&P 500: Consumer Discretionary(XLY), Consumer Staples(XLP), Energy(XLE), Financials(XLF), Health Care(XLV), Industrials(XLI), Materials(XLB), Real Estate(XLRE), Technology(XLK), Utilities(XLU)¶

Purpose¶

In this tutorial, our aim is to explore whether there is any connection between the day-to-day price changes of 10 S&P500 sector-based ETFs during the past 5 years and the price movements of 10-year bonds, the Euro Index, the US Dollar Index, gold, and crude oil on the same day. Additionally, we will analyze if there are any differences in how these indicators impact each sector. It's crucial to note that we will be looking into short-term price movements, not long-term trends. The importance of this project lies in its potential to help investors mitigate risks in the complex and intertwined world of the market, where they may face significant challenges. Ultimately, this study intends to provide investors with a foundation for identifying suitable risk management strategies and making informed investment decisions.¶

Data Collection¶

To start off this tutorial, we'll gather all the required data and organize it into a Pandas DataFrame. The data we'll be working with pertains to daily price changes over a 5-year period. We sourced historical data on S&P 500 sector-based ETFs from Yahoo Finance and obtained historical data on 5 indices from Investing.com. Once the data was collected, we made some adjustments to column names and converted the dates into datetime format.¶

As you can see, the "Change %" column in all of the dataframes has a data type of "object" because the elements in this column are in the format of "float%". To proceed with our analysis, we need to remove the "%" symbol and convert these values into the "float64" data type.¶

After removing outliers using z-scores from each dataframe, we can recreate the same histogram, which provides a clearer understanding that the Change% for all indices follows a normal distribution.¶
Next, we will remove the "Vol." column from all five dataframes. While trading volume is an important indicator for measuring market sentiment in commodities, indexes, stocks, and other trading assets, the available volume data in this dataframe is sourced only from Investing.com, which may not provide accurate volume information due to variations across different exchanges. Therefore, it is necessary to exclude this column from our analysis.¶
In [55]:

In [56]:

df_eur_index = df_eur_index.drop(columns=['EUR Index Vol'])
df_gold = df_gold.drop(columns=['Gold Vol'])
In the same vein, we will remove the "High" and "Low" columns from all five dataframes. As this analysis focuses only on the price range between the opening and closing times of the market, the daily high and low prices are not relevant. While these are important factors for a more precise analysis of price movements, hourly data for the S&P500 sectors and these five indicators is not available. Therefore, the best possible analysis is to observe the difference between the opening and closing prices.¶
Since we already have the "Change%" column that represents the percentage increase or decrease from the opening to the closing price, we can drop the "Open" and "Closing" columns as they provide redundant information.¶

The chart above shows the price movements of all the 10 sector ETFs over the past 5 years. Although they may appear similar when viewed over a long period, a closer examination reveals that they are actually quite distinct. Even during periods of general growth, one ETF may experience a significantly larger price movement than others, and there may be instances when they move in different directions. As a result, it's crucial to analyze the price movements separately for each sector, as they exhibit unique patterns of movement.¶
We will create a chart that displays both the price movements and trading volumes of each sector ETF over the past 5 years. Trading volume represents the transaction fees and serves as a measure of market overheating. By examining trading volume together with price movements, we can identify the timing when traders are most active and the corresponding price movements.¶

    # Find outliers

    # Remove outliers
    df = df.drop(outliers.index)

Machine Learning and Hypothesis Testing¶

In the next step, we will perform multiple regression analysis and hypothesis testing. To create a model in a more efficient way, we will combine all the dataframes for the same date and create a new dataframe, df_merged. Using the statsmodels.api, we will develop a multiple regression analysis model that uses Oil Change%, Gold Change%, T-bonds Change%, USD Index Change%, and EUR Index Change% as explanatory variables and predicts the daily change rate of the S&P 500 sector ETF as the response variable. We will then output a summary report and conduct hypothesis testing while examining the results of the multiple regression analysis. We will start off with xly as a response variable. The null hypothesis is that "there is no slope in the regression line."¶

We used xly (Consumer Discretionary Select Sector) as the response variable and obtained what appears to be an ideal model. However, since the demand and supply of stocks are generally influenced by other stocks, this is a natural result. We can try to improve the model by removing explanatory variables with p-values higher than the significance level. These variables are EUR Index Change %, USD Index Change %, T-bonds Index Change %, and xlp. What's interesting is that the model shows that the change rates of gold and oil are functioning as explanatory variables. This could be explained by the fact that gold is often considered a safe-haven asset that attracts demand during market downturns. The Consumer Discretionary Select Sector comprises service companies such as automobiles, apparel, hotels, and restaurants, which are correlated with economic prosperity. Therefore, it makes sense that the coefficient for gold is negative when xly is used as the response variable.¶

Insight and Conclusion¶

In this tutorial, we investigated how the daily price movements of 10 different sector ETFs are influenced by the movements of 5 indices, gold, bonds, interest rates, the US dollar index, and the euro index. However, we were unable to achieve the expected results. The main issue was the limited number of explanatory variables. Additionally, although we needed to consider factors such as inflation indicators, there was no way to predict their short-term movements. The most commonly used inflation indicator, CPI, is updated only once a month, making it impossible to incorporate it into our analysis. As mentioned earlier, the unavailability of datasets on trading volumes and hourly price movements was also a contributing factor that hindered our initial analysis.¶
In summary, the shorter the term price movement, the more random the walk tends to be. Analyzing financial markets is a challenging task due to their complexity, as they are influenced by numerous factors. Nonetheless, we did recognize a correlation between the sector ETFs, which is a positive outcome. Therefore, it is still appropriate to examine the supply and demand of other stocks to a certain extent in order to predict short-term price movements.¶
In the future, if we have another opportunity to analyze the financial markets, we would like to focus on long-term price movements as they are relatively easier to obtain data sets for.¶
